# Linguistic Simulator

> A linguistic autobiography presented as an interactive web application.  
> Live demo → [zansah.github.io/linguistic-simulator](https://zansah.github.io/linguistic-simulator)

---

## What This Project Is

This web app models how a single speaker — me — shifts between different varieties of American English depending on **context**, **audience**, and **situation**. You type a sentence, pick a mode (Academic, Casual, Family, Gaming, Formal Email, or Texting/Slang), and the app rewrites it to reflect how I would actually say it in that setting. A pulsing orb plays the result back using text-to-speech.

Concepts in this project are: 

| Concept | How it shows up in the app |
|---|---|
| **Register variation** | Formal text to informal slang |
| **Code-switching** | Switching between different linguistic varieties |
| **Audience design** | The transformation engine rewrites sentences based on who the imagined listener is |
| **Pragmatic variation** | Directness, implicature, and politeness all shift across modes |

---

## Linguistic Autobiography — Reflection

### What varieties of American English do I have personal familiarity with?

I've been exposed to several distinct varieties of English, this web app models the ones I interact with most frenquently:

**Standard American English** is what I learned in school and is used in professional settings. Examples of this would be "I would argue that..." or "I am not entirely certain" sounds formal.

**Casual American English** the type of language I use with friends. 

**Family speech** the language I use with my parents. Uses a mix of English, French, and Twi (Akan) words, and is more diret than casual speech. 
---

### What social factors shaped the way I speak English?

Factors:

- **Educational context** — years of schooling and formal writing.
- **Peer communities** — friend groups, online spaces, and gaming communities each defined a distinct version.
- **Audience awareness** — I grew up code-switching consciously: I knew early that you talk differently to a teacher versus a friend versus a grandparent.
---

### Why I'm taking this course

Factors:

- **Affects of social media  on slang**
- **Code-switching** — Recently I took a class on Migration across Latin America and thats led me to be interested in the ways that language and idenity intersect.

---

### What am I hoping to get out of this course?

Gain a better understanding of linguistic in general, as it appears in fields like language and human-computer interaction. 
